title: For Sale:  World War II Japanese Type 30 Bayone

title: For Sale:  PWS Modern Musket 16"
postcontent: Selling My PWS Modern Musket DI rifle in .223/5.56 (.223 wylde chamber). This is PWS's first foray into the direct impingement market. This is NOT your standard DI rifle, as PWS puts their custom touches on even their DI gun that separates it from the rest of the crowd.The bolt carrier group is PWS’s Enhanced Bolt Carrier. It is precision machined and isonite treated (just like the barrel). The bolt carrier has increased mass (it is significantly thicker than a standard BCG) which should both extend dwell time and slightly delay unlock. What this means is that it allows the chamber pressure to be reduced making extraction easier and thus accumulating less wear and tear on the system.There are a number of gaps and channels between skid pads on the BCG which provides fewer points of contact. With fewer points there should be less overall friction, and this should reduce the accumulation of residue and grime, as well as further reduce wear and tear.The Buffer Tube, machined from a single piece of 6061 aluminum, is one of the important features. It has a lip that extends into the receiver and provides support against carrier tilt (not as important since this is a direct impingement system). It has four drain holes to prevent hydrostatic locking of the reciprocating buffer, and is fluted to shed debris. It uses a standard carbine length H2 buffer and spring. The difference between this buffer and more commonly available ones is that the buffer itself is a tungsten weight housed in a steel body, coated in nickel Teflon. So it is both heavier and slicker. The tube uses a hex bolt to help align the tube to the lower receiver and two locking allen heads at the top to keep the buffer tube from rotating on the lower. If you are not familiar with the PWS buffer tube, what this boils down to is: No. More. Castle. Nut. On the Modern Musket this buffer tube also has a six-position stop, allowing for standard AR collapsible stocks to be attached.The barrel is a 1:8 twist that's been isonite coated, for maximum longevity and accuracy. The Rail is a PWS keymod rail, which is EXTREMELY lightweght. The muzzle device is PWS's factory FSC556 muzzle break/flash hider which does an excellent job at keeping muzzle rise down.The trigger is an ALG combat defense trigger, which tuned by Geissele for smooth take up. The charging handle is a BCM gunfighter, for easy of manipulating the weapon.scope is a 4x Primary Arms sitting on a American Defense quick release mount. Also has quality backup flip up sites Comes with a nice hard case, 6 pmags of assorted capacities 10,30,40It is precision machined and isonite treated (just like the barrel). title: For Sale:  Hunter,Shooter,Collector
postcontent: I know... I know, you've been advised to move to 6.5 Creedmoor, right?  Even though the .270 is faster and harder hitting?  Before you buy that 6.5 line of hype, think about what you really need and want in a rifle and cartridge.  I can understand if you're recoil sensitive and fear the .270 and 30.06 rifles.  But if you're not, keep reading for a great deal on a shooter/collector setup. Ruger INTERNATIONAL (full length Mannlicher stock) RSI M77 shot very little and taking up room in the safe for far too long.  Produced only for a short time in center fire calibers.  It has an original Redfield Company scope, and there were not a lot of these rifles made.  It was purchased in the eighties for an Elk hunt that never transpired due to health problem.  This is the International model with the long Mannlcher wood stock.  I have seen them, though rarely, in other calibers and this one is .270 Win, so ammo is easy to find all over, a fast, flat shooting and highly respected hunting caliber.   It will come with ammo and some once fired brass as well as reloading dies.  It has a nice leather sling, too.  So, is this a DEAL?  BET on it.  Cash is best, but a quality firearm is never unwelcome.    Thanks for looking.  Face to face, guys, no shipping.  Still here, a pending sale fell through when a guy brought a really rough trade to the table and then tried to tell me I HAD to honor it.  I should take junk for an excellent rifle?  We had no deal, only conversation and bullshit.  He asked for photos, I sent photos.  I asked for photos, he sent a stock advertisement photo for M1... not even close to the garbage he brought to meet me.  I would have accepted an excellent M1, added money for an ACR... but I can find junk along the highway.  I might even take HK hammer fired pistol as part trade as in P30, P2000, or as even trade HK Mk23.  But no junk, please.  If you don't have cash, then I need to see real and recent photos of your trade firearm as ell as your thoughts on what you expect me to accept in terms of what your trade is worth.

bought it recently and haven't been able to shoot it until recently when I put twenty (now more than sixty) rounds through it with not a hitch using the iron sights and shooting into two clay pigeons and their pieces at one hundred yards offhand.  Must have been good ammo (Walmart's cheapest) or a really good rifle because I built a small pile of fired brass to my right rear in about twelve inches circle and didn't have to chase brass, broke three clap pigeons and the pieces, had a riot doing it. Next trip to range, off hand and feeling a little better, I was shooting the petals from the little white vine flowers on the hundred yard berm. Stock has been modified slightly with a slip on recoil pad, and the original steel butt plate is missing beneath the rubber pad.  I wasn't shooting for a group, but I was not disappointed, either.  I'm glad I finally got a chance to shoot the rifle.  Did a field-type clean on it only to this point.   FACE TO FACE IN JAX, and cash only, please.  The rifle performed well enough first time out that I won't be disappointed if I keep it.  I chose 'Norinco' as manufacturer because I could not find Federal Ordnance listed as choice.   Thanks for looking.  Note:  last week a friend and I visited the range on a day of light rain and made under one inch groups and even shot the petals off some of the viny flowers on the hundred yard berm.  It's looking more and more like a higher price or keeper.  Trades?  I would consider an enhanced Bushmaster ACR.

The front sight is fixed near the muzzle, and on the right side of the barrel is the bayonet lug.  Three steel barrel bands hold the stock to the barrel, the middle band holding the sling swivel. The rear sight is a 3-¼” ladder sight, with a secondary offset notch for long range shooting. The bore is in very good condition. The receiver is in good condition, with very few dings. The hammer and block are in very good condition, with very little wear. Note the secondary firing pin hole for use with rimfire cartridges. The walnut stock runs the length of the barrel to the bayonet lug.  There are many dings and scratches, but the Danish crown can still be seen stamped into the buttstock.  The buttstock has a lightly patinated buttplate, a unit marking disk, and a sling swivel. The Danish crown is stamped on the barrel, receiver, barrel bands, stock, hammer, and buttplate. The serial number is stamped on the left side of the barrel and the underside of the buttstock.  Overall length is 50-½”, length of pull is 12-¾”, and weight is 8.6 lbs. Our stock number is #A273. Willing to ship anywhere in the US, buyer pays freight and insurance.
